Thallium wrote:Isn't there an atmospheric processor on the planet by 2120? Maybe that's why it looks so much darker and more dismal in Alien; the processor is screwing with the atmosphere itself, causing storms, things like that.No. LV-426 is, according to dialog in Aliens, "an unsurveyed planet at that time" (where "that time" == Alien timeframe). The terraforming effort and the Hadley's Hope colony are established in the interstitial period between the two films.edited to add--If Prometheus does take place on LV-426, it brings up several interesting twists:* It's always been assumed that the reason the Nostromo is diverted to LV-426 to pick up the alien is because WY had previously intercepted the same transmission Dallas mentions at the beginning of Alien, and then arranged for the next available ship (the Nostromo) to pop down and check it out. If Prometheus takes place on LV-426, then WY has advanced knowledge of exactly what's down there.* It's always been assumed that the derelict is the source of the transmission. Indeed, the "Alien" novelization by Alan Dean Foster (based off of an earlier O'Bannon-heavy draft of the script prior to a lot of Giler's adjustments and Giger's alien design being finalized) has the crew actually locating the transmitter and shutting it off. However, it's possible that the transmitter isn't an alien transmitter at all--it's possible it's the distress beacon from the downed Prometheus warning everyone away, and MOTHER (or MU-TH-UR, take your pick) easily decodes it because it is in fact not alien in origin.* On the other hand, that's clearly a retcon, since scenes were shot in Alien showing the crew listening to the alien transmission and it is indeed very alien. At least five different variations of the audio were created, with one being featured on the original Aliens Collection DVD box set and a second one on the Quadrilogy and BluRay releases. The scene was cut, but it demonstrates that at least in 1978, the intent was that the signal be alien and not human.
